subsection.p:
Now reverse the order: I= \int_0^1\int_0^x e^{x^2}\,dy\,dx. The inner integral is now easy because e^{x^2} is constant with respect to y: \int_0^x e^{x^2}\,dy = xe^{x^2}. So I= \int_0^1 xe^{x^2}\,dx. Let u=x^2, \qquad du=2x\,dx. Then
I \amp= \frac12\int_0^1 e^u\,du \amp= \frac12(e-1).
Thus \boxed{ \int_0^1\int_y^1 e^{x^2}\,dx\,dy = \frac{e-1}{2}. }

